metadata.name: NEBELWALD #4
metadata.description:
NEBELWALD is the first series of about 10 different tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years. 

This project explores a minimalist approach to tree naturalism using a recursive algorithm and includes three traits: a density layer of fog, a measure of tree growth, and the softness of snowfall.

Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png.

Artist notes:

Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

Once I experienced it in a dense fog, which was amazing! beautiful and mysterious at the same time. This has definitely inspired the NEBELWALD work series.

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: http://lumicon.de/e-art/project/nebelwald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.

metadata.name: Moonlines #54
metadata.description:
The Moonlines project explores the combination of minimalist forms and basic rules to create complex images.

It uses a simplistic approach to combine 4 sets of parallel lines and a main shape in its center.

The overlapping and intersection of slightly slanted lines can generate beautiful interferences that result in complex moiré effects.

metadata.name: GRAVITATE #6
metadata.description:
Each piece in this collection is made from the simple concept of layering grids of circles. The varying grid sizes, circle sizes, positions and colors combine to create interesting dithering effects. There are seven color palettes in the algorithm and these range from low contrast, muted palettes (e.g. Mystic Sands) to high contrast, super saturated palettes (e.g. Inferno).

- - -

GRAVITATE is my first generative art collection and was made using only p5.js.

- - -

Commands:
Press `1` to save a low-res PNG 1200x1800
Press `2` to save a high-res PNG 4800x7200

Note that it may take up to 10secs for the image render to complete.

metadata.name: Element #148
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: walkinthepark #10
metadata.description:
Mazes are almost entierly context-free. The mazes of `walkinthepark` have no entrance or exit. Not all of them are solvable. Any resemblance to reality is pure coincidence.

All features are distributed equally:
- weave - The internal pattern of sub-mazes.
- density - The density of the sub-mazes.
- color - Yep.
- aim - How big the biggest sub-maze can get.
- bars - How connected sub-mazes are.
- stroke - The randomness of lines.
- skew - How much some sub-mazes are rotated.
- grain - How many sub-mazes are rotated.

@balidani, Dec 2021

metadata.name: pantonX.3 #266
metadata.description:
pantonX.3
is the third drop of the zukuNFT project, which is dedicated to geometric and minimalist standards of early geometric art.
inspired by the "bauhaus grundkurs" based on the didactic concepts of the bauhaus (1919-1933) and its teachings by johannes itten, paul klee, wassily kandinsky, lászló moholy-nagy and josef albers. the preliminary courses and their basic design tasks dealt syntactically with circle, line and square as well as color, and contrasts.

i am a visual artist and have worked in the field of coding since the early years of processing.
always loved geometric and minimalist art, bauhaus, de stijl, piet mondrian, sol leWitt -- just to name a few -- and last but not least verner panton, have had a influence on my artistic work.

metadata.name: Knockout #31
metadata.description:
An exploration of screen printing techniques and how these effects can be achieved in generative work. The halftone effect works by placing very small dots next to each other to give the illusion of new shades and hues. Each Knockout samples three colors for the main composition and runs small sections of the canvas back through the machine after shuffling the base palette. The secondary passes vary in size, creating interesting emergent patterns on the overlap.

Press 's' in live view to save a .png

Built and tested with Chrome on Apple silicon. Some outputs may take up to 20s on slower machines.

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #284
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #209
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Perspective #21
metadata.description:
A few primitives and a lot of points.

Warning: This piece is GPU intensive, it may not render on lower end devices.

Keys
s: Take a screenshot
space: Pause/Play the animation.
r: Play a new animation
↑: Increase point alpha
↓: Decrease point alpha
→: Increase point density
←: Decrease point density

URL Params
w: Width of the canvas - (ex, w=1024) - [0-2048]
h: Height of the canvas - (ex, h=1024) - [0-2048]
a: To set the alpha for the points - [0.0-1.0]
p: To set the total number of points to draw (in millions) [1-8]
s: Make the visual static - (ex, s=1)
